div.p:
Besides, no Man can so well and fully understand Happiness, as he that is Happy; 
                        〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                     , saith Poltinus. What a Man is in Disposition and Habit, that he knows; and not that which he reads in Books, but hath not prov'd in himself.

If any should here interrupt me with Tantum Religio potuit suadere malorum;

                        Objection. 
                      and tell me, that the setting up God's Kingdom has been the great Disturber of the Peace of the World; and that no Place on Earth is fuller of Wars and Unquietness, than Christendom. I make this short Reply; 
                        Reply. 
                      That it was not Religion, but somewhat that passed under that Name, of which that Observation is made.
